    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1028843769" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1028843769" />
    <a title="Tushar Mangl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16149354-tushar-mangl"><img alt="Tushar Mangl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1476510451p2/16149354.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1028843769?book_show_action=true">Aug 16, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tushar Mangl" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tushar Mangl" href="/user/show/16149354-tushar-mangl">Tushar Mangl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1028843769" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18383224306317127728">Ratna Vira&apos;s debut book is one hell of a story. I mean, I usually have limited confidence in Indian literature of modern times. But this once, exceeds all expectations. I get a unique story to read, presented in a very lucid style. I of course being a North Indian, formerly of a joint family can very well connect with the story. The characters are penned very well, the backgrounds painted like an artist&apos;s rendition. <br/><br/>The layering of mother daughter relationship is the crux of the book. Our chief </span>
  <span id="freeText18383224306317127728" style="display:none">Ratna Vira's debut book is one hell of a story. I mean, I usually have limited confidence in Indian literature of modern times. But this once, exceeds all expectations. I get a unique story to read, presented in a very lucid style. I of course being a North Indian, formerly of a joint family can very well connect with the story. The characters are penned very well, the backgrounds painted like an artist's rendition. <br /><br />The layering of mother daughter relationship is the crux of the book. Our chief protagonist Aranya's relationship with her daughter, her relation with her own mother, then mother with her mother etc.So many mother daughter relationships. All layered well. As the court processes in India happen slow and are often tiresome, the story too lagged down in some places. It seemed that the author is trying to stuff too much in one book. Also some parts about mother harassing her daughter sounded repetitive. The story at least for me lacked strong male characters. The one strong one I found was already dead.<br /><br />All in all a different yet a good read. <br /><br />_________________________________________________<br />Received a complimentary copy from the author, via the GoodReads Giveaway program </span>
  <a data-text-id="18383224306317127728" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


